				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">DRW wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">[code]<br />  LDX $0104, X ; Loads &quot;length&quot; into X.</div><br />This addressing mode doesn't exist, see <!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html#LDX">http://www.obelisk.demon.co.uk/6502/reference.html#LDX</a><!-- m --><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If the stack starts at $0100, why do I have to get the most recent stack value with $010<span style="text-decoration: underline">3</span> + X? I assume that the first value in the stack might be the stack pointer itself, so that the actual stack variables start at $0101. But why $0103?</div><br />Stack pointer is not at $100, it's a register inside the CPU itself. As for why $103, consider this example:<br /><br />Let's say stack pointer starts out as $FF, i.e. SP = $FF, i.e. it points to $1FF. Now let's say the caller pushes two values on the stack, so the bytes are placed at $1FF and $1FE and SP = $FD after. When you call a function, two more bytes (the return value) get pushed on the stack, so SP becomes $FB. And how do we get from the stack pointer value, $FB, to the parameter at $1FE? By adding $1FE - $FB = $103.</div>

					
